NBA Team Pattern Analysis - Abstract

Lucas Little CSCA5632 University of Colorado Boulder

Project Overview

This project uses unsupervised learning techniques to discover natural patterns and team archetypes in NBA data. The analysis leverages data from several sources:

  • NBA Shots Dataset
  • NBA Injury Stats Dataset
  • NBA/ABA/BAA Team Statistics Dataset

Analysis Approaches

The project employs three main unsupervised learning approaches:

  1. Clustering Analysis

    • K-means clustering to identify team archetypes
    • Hierarchical clustering to understand relationships between playing styles

  2. Dimensionality Reduction

    • PCA to identify key performance components
    • t-SNE for non-linear visualization of team relationships

  3. Anomaly Detection

    • Isolation Forest to identify unusual team performances
    • Analysis of outlier seasons and strategies

Research Goals

Through these techniques, we aim to:

  • Discover natural groupings of NBA teams based on playing style
  • Identify patterns in successful team strategies
  • Understand how injuries affect team performance patterns
  • Track the evolution of NBA playing styles over time

This unsupervised learning approach provides deeper insights into NBA team patterns and relationships compared to traditional supervised classification methods.

  • Shot Locations: To identify shooting pattern clusters and offensive strategies

NBA Team Pattern Analysis - Data Cleaning

Overview

This notebook transforms raw NBA data into clean, analysis-ready datasets. High-quality data cleaning is crucial for unsupervised learning - if our data is inconsistent or noisy, our pattern detection will be unreliable.

Why Careful Data Cleaning Matters

  1. Historical Consistency Challenges

    • NBA statistical tracking has evolved significantly since 1951
    • Three-point line introduced in 1979 changed offensive statistics
    • Shot clock introduction in 1954 affected pace metrics
    • Need to normalize stats across different eras

  2. Team Identity Issues

    • Franchises relocate (e.g., Seattle SuperSonics Oklahoma City Thunder)
    • Teams change names (e.g., Washington Bullets Washington Wizards)
    • Different datasets use varying team abbreviations
    • Need consistent team identifiers across all data sources

  3. Statistical Standardization Requirements

    • Per-game vs. per-possession statistics
    • Adjusting for pace differences between eras
    • Normalizing counting stats vs. percentages
    • Creating comparable metrics across seasons

Data Sources and Cleaning Steps

1. NBA/ABA/BAA Stats Dataset

Player Season Information

  • Raw Data Challenges:

    • Inconsistent team names (e.g., 'PHO' vs 'PHX' for Phoenix)
    • Mixed league data (NBA, ABA, BAA)
    • Missing conference information
    • Incomplete statistical records

  • Cleaning Steps:

    1. Standardize team names using mapping dictionary
    2. Filter for NBA-only data (post-merger statistics)
    3. Add conference information based on season
    4. Handle missing values with appropriate strategies:
      • Use era averages for missing counting stats
      • Remove records with critical missing data
      • Interpolate where historically appropriate

Team Statistics Per Game

  • Raw Data Issues:

    • Inconsistent statistical categories over time
    • Different calculation methodologies by era
    • Varying season lengths affecting totals

  • Standardization Process:

    1. Normalize all stats to per-100 possessions
    2. Create consistent statistical categories
    3. Adjust for rule changes (e.g., three-point line)
    4. Generate comparable metrics across eras

2. NBA Injury Statistics

  • Data Range: 1951-2023

  • Cleaning Requirements:

    1. Standardize injury classifications
    2. Normalize team names to match other datasets
    3. Create consistent duration metrics
    4. Generate team-level injury impact scores

  • Derived Metrics:

    • Games missed per season
    • Impact-weighted injury scores
    • Roster availability percentage
    • Key player injury impact

Data Quality Validation

Feature Preparation Checks

  1. Scale Normalization

    • All numeric features scaled to comparable ranges
    • Prevents large-scale features from dominating clustering
    • Example: Converting raw points (100s) to z-scores

  2. Missing Data Strategy

    • < 5% missing: Era-based mean imputation
    • 5-15% missing: Advanced imputation (KNN)

    • 15% missing: Feature evaluation for removal

    • Critical features: Remove records if missing

  3. Outlier Processing

    • Statistical outliers vs. genuine exceptional performances
    • Keep legitimate outliers (e.g., Wilt's 100-point game)
    • Remove data entry errors (impossible values)
    • Flag extreme values for anomaly detection

  4. Correlation Analysis

    • Identify highly correlated features (>0.85)
    • Remove redundant features
    • Preserve interpretability for analysis
    • Document removal decisions"

NBA Team Pattern Analysis - Feature Engineering

Overview

This notebook transforms basic NBA statistics into sophisticated features that reveal team patterns and strategies. Each feature is carefully designed to capture specific aspects of team performance and style.

Feature Engineering Goals

  1. Capture Strategic Identity

    • Reveal how teams actually play, not just how well they play
    • Identify philosophical approaches to the game
    • Distinguish between similar performing teams with different styles

  2. Enable Pattern Discovery

    • Create features that cluster naturally
    • Balance detail and noise reduction
    • Ensure features are interpretable

Feature Categories and Calculations

1. Playing Style Features

Offensive Style Metrics

  • Pace Factor (How fast teams play)

    pace = 48 * ((Poss_Team + Poss_Opp) / (2 * (Team_Min / 5)))
    • Above 100: Fast-paced team
    • Below 95: Methodical approach
    • Examples: 2019 Bucks (105.3), 2004 Pistons (87.9)

  • Shot Distribution Score (Where teams get their points)

    paint_rate = Paint_FGA / Total_FGA
three_rate = Three_FGA / Total_FGA
mid_rate = Mid_Range_FGA / Total_FGA
shot_entropy = -sum(p * log(p) for p in [paint_rate, three_rate, mid_rate])
    • Higher entropy: Diverse attack (2014 Spurs: 1.57)
    • Lower entropy: Specialized approach (2016 Rockets: 1.12)

  • Ball Movement Rating (How teams create shots)

    movement_score = (Assists/FGM) * (Passes/Possession) * Secondary_Assist_Rate
    • Above 2.5: Motion offense (2014 Spurs)
    • Below 1.5: Isolation heavy (2006 Lakers)

Defensive Identity Features

  • Pressure Index (Defensive aggression)

    pressure = (Steals + Deflections) / Defensive_Possessions * 100
    • Above 15: High pressure (2004 Pistons)
    • Below 10: Conservative (2019 Bucks)

  • Protection Metrics (Rim defense)

    rim_protection = (Blocks/Opp_Paint_FGA) * (1 - Opp_Paint_FG%)
    • Above 0.3: Elite protection (2008 Celtics)
    • Below 0.2: Perimeter focused (2017 Cavaliers)

2. Team Composition Features

Roster Construction Metrics

  • Experience Profile

    exp_score = (weighted_avg_experience * veteran_ratio) / rookie_ratio
    • Above 5.0: Veteran team (2013 Spurs)
    • Below 2.0: Young core (2021 Grizzlies)

  • Depth Analysis

    depth_score = entropy([mins/total_mins for mins in rotation_minutes])
    • Above 2.2: Deep rotation (2014 Spurs)
    • Below 1.8: Star dependent (2017 Thunder)

Health and Availability

  • Impact-Adjusted Injury Score
    injury_impact = sum(player_impact * games_missed for each injury)
    • Weights injuries by player importance
    • Normalized to per-season scale
    • Accounts for timing of injuries

3. Performance Pattern Features

Efficiency Metrics

  • True Shooting Gravity

    ts_gravity = (TS% - League_Avg_TS%) * Usage_Rate
    • Measures efficiency relative to volume
    • Identifies efficient high-volume teams

  • Defensive Versatility Score

    def_versatility = std([def_rating_vs_style for each_style in ['fast', 'slow', 'post', 'perimeter']])
    • Lower scores: Adaptable defense
    • Higher scores: Matchup dependent

Consistency Features

  • Performance Stability Index
    stability = 1 / std([game_score for each_game])
    • Above 2.0: Consistent performers
    • Below 1.5: High variance teams

1. Data Loading and Initial Processing

  • Load cleaned datasets
  • Verify data quality
  • Set up feature calculation pipeline

NBA Team Pattern Analysis - Team Archetypes

Overview

This notebook discovers and analyzes natural team archetypes in the NBA using clustering techniques. By identifying distinct playing styles and strategic groupings, we can understand how different approaches to the game emerge and evolve.

Analysis Goals

  1. Discover Natural Team Groupings

    • Find distinct playing styles that emerge naturally
    • Understand what makes each archetype unique
    • Identify how many meaningful archetypes exist

  2. Analyze Strategic Relationships

    • Map relationships between different playing styles
    • Understand strategic distances between teams
    • Track how teams move between archetypes

  3. Validate Findings

    • Compare different clustering approaches
    • Ensure archetypes are meaningful
    • Verify consistency across methods

Expected Insights

  • Strategic Diversity: How many distinct ways are there to play NBA basketball?
  • Success Patterns: Do certain archetypes consistently lead to more success?
  • Evolution Trends: How have dominant archetypes changed over time?
  • Team Identity: Which teams maintain consistent archetypes vs. those that adapt?

Methodology

We use two complementary clustering approaches:

  1. K-means Clustering

    • Finds distinct team archetypes
    • Each team belongs to exactly one archetype
    • Optimal number of archetypes determined by elbow method

  2. Hierarchical Clustering

    • Shows relationships between archetypes
    • Reveals strategic similarity hierarchy
    • Validates k-means findings

1. K-Means Clustering - Finding Natural Team Groups

Determining Optimal Number of Archetypes

We use the elbow method to find how many distinct team archetypes naturally exist in the data. The optimal number occurs where adding more clusters provides diminishing returns in explaining team variation.

Typical interpretations:

  • 3-4 clusters: Broad strategic categories (e.g., offensive vs. defensive focus)
  • 5-6 clusters: More nuanced strategic distinctions
  • 7+ clusters: Very fine-grained differences that may not be meaningful

# Elbow Method Plot
model = KMeans(random_state=42)
visualizer = KElbowVisualizer(model, k=(2, 10))
visualizer.fit(features_scaled)
optimal_k = visualizer.elbow_value_

plt.ylabel('Within-Group Variance')
plt.show()

print("\nInterpretation:")
print(f"The elbow method suggests {optimal_k} distinct playing styles in the NBA,")
print("balancing between capturing meaningful differences and avoiding over-segmentation.")

Common archetype examples:

  • Three-point focused teams (high three-point rate, high offensive rating)

# Fit K-means with optimal k
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=optimal_k, random_state=42)
cluster_labels = kmeans.fit_predict(features_scaled)
data_clean['archetype'] = cluster_labels

# Create archetype characteristics heatmap
archetype_means = pd.DataFrame(kmeans.cluster_centers_, columns=features.columns)
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 8))
sns.heatmap(archetype_means, cmap='coolwarm', center=0, annot=True, fmt='.2f')
plt.title('Team Archetype Characteristics')
plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Display teams in each archetype
print("\nTeams by Archetype:")
for i in range(optimal_k):
    archetype_teams = data_clean[data_clean['archetype'] == i]
    print(f"\nArchetype {i} Teams:")
    print("Key characteristics:")
    # Get top 3 distinguishing features
    characteristics = archetype_means.iloc[i].nlargest(3)
    for feat, value in characteristics.items():
        print(f"- High {feat}: {value:.2f}")
    print("\nTeams:")
    print(archetype_teams[['team', 'season']].to_string(index=False))

Overview

Analysis Goals

    • Understand which metrics matter most
    • Reduce complexity while preserving insights

    • Map how teams move through strategic space
    • Identify trends in strategic changes
    • Understand what drives strategic shifts

    • Show how different strategies relate
    • Find natural strategic groupings
    • Identify strategic innovations

Expected Insights

  • Evolution Patterns: How do successful strategies spread through the league?
  • Innovation Drivers: What causes teams to change their strategic approach?
  • Success Factors: Which strategic shifts lead to improved performance?

Methodology

We use two complementary dimensionality reduction techniques:

  1. Principal Component Analysis (PCA)

1. Principal Component Analysis

Identifying Key Strategic Components

PCA helps us understand the fundamental dimensions of NBA strategy. Each component represents a combination of metrics that tend to vary together.

Common strategic components often include:

  • Offensive vs. defensive focus
  • Pace and transition play
  • Inside vs. outside scoring
  • Ball movement vs. isolation

The explained variance ratio tells us how many components we need to capture most strategic variation.

In[2]:
# Fit PCA
pca = PCA()
pca_result = pca.fit_transform(features_scaled)

# Plot explained variance
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(range(1, len(pca.explained_variance_ratio_) + 1),
         np.cumsum(pca.explained_variance_ratio_), 'bo-')
plt.xlabel('Number of Strategic Components')
plt.ylabel('Cumulative Explained Variance')
plt.title('Key Strategic Components Importance')
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

# Calculate number of components needed for 80% variance
n_components_80 = np.where(np.cumsum(pca.explained_variance_ratio_) >= 0.8)[0][0] + 1
print(f"Number of components needed to explain 80% of strategic variance: {n_components_80}")
print("\nInterpretation:")
print(f"NBA team strategy can be largely understood through {n_components_80} key dimensions,")
print("suggesting a balance between complexity and fundamental patterns.")

# Fit t-SNE
tsne = TSNE(random_state=42)

# Create visualization DataFrame
viz_df = pd.DataFrame({
    'x': tsne_result[:, 0],
    'y': tsne_result[:, 1],
    'team': data_clean['team'],
    'season': data_clean['season']
})

# Plot t-SNE results with team trajectories
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 10))

# Plot points for all teams
plt.scatter(viz_df['x'], viz_df['y'], alpha=0.6)

# Add team labels and connect points for same team across seasons
for team in viz_df['team'].unique():
    team_data = viz_df[viz_df['team'] == team].sort_values('season')
    
    # Draw lines connecting consecutive seasons
    plt.plot(team_data['x'], team_data['y'], '-', alpha=0.4)
    
    # Add labels for first and last season
    first_season = team_data.iloc[0]
    last_season = team_data.iloc[-1]
    
    plt.annotate(f"{team} ({first_season['season']})",
                 (first_season['x'], first_season['y']),
                 fontsize=8)
    plt.annotate(f"{team} ({last_season['season']})",
                 (last_season['x'], last_season['y']),
                 fontsize=8)

plt.title('Team Strategy Evolution Over Time')
plt.xlabel('Strategic Dimension 1')
plt.ylabel('Strategic Dimension 2')
plt.show()

# Analyze strategic shifts
print("\nNotable Strategic Evolutions:")
# Calculate largest strategic shifts
for team in viz_df['team'].unique():
    team_data = viz_df[viz_df['team'] == team].sort_values('season')
    if len(team_data) > 1:
        start = team_data.iloc[0]
        end = team_data.iloc[-1]
        distance = np.sqrt((end['x'] - start['x'])**2 + (end['y'] - start['y'])**2)
        if distance > np.percentile(distance, 90):
            print(f"- {team}: Major strategic shift from {start['season']} to {end['season']}")

1. Identifying Exceptional Teams

Anomaly Detection

Using Isolation Forest to find teams that stand out from typical patterns. These could be:

# Fit Isolation Forest
iso_forest = IsolationForest(random_state=42, contamination=0.1)
outliers = iso_forest.fit_predict(features_scaled)
data_clean['is_exceptional'] = outliers == -1

# Identify exceptional teams
exceptional_teams = data_clean[data_clean['is_exceptional']]

# Calculate feature importance scores

feature_importance = pd.Series(np.mean(feature_scores), index=features.columns)

Strategic Differences

Compare exceptional teams to league averages to understand:

  • What makes them unique
  • How they achieve success
  • Trade-offs they make

Common patterns in exceptional teams:

  • Extreme specialization in one area
  • Novel combinations of existing strategies
  • Early adoption of emerging trends

# Calculate average features for exceptional vs normal teams
exceptional_avg = features[data_clean['is_exceptional']].mean()
normal_avg = features[~data_clean['is_exceptional']].mean()
feature_diff = exceptional_avg - normal_avg

# Plot feature differences
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
feature_diff.sort_values().plot(kind='bar')
plt.title('How Exceptional Teams Differ from Average')
plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')
plt.axhline(y=0, color='r', linestyle='-', alpha=0.3)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Print top differentiating features
print("\nKey Characteristics of Exceptional Teams:")
print("\nStrengths (Features Higher than Average):")
for feat, val in feature_diff.nlargest(5).items():
    print(f"- {feat}: +{val:.2f} standard deviations")
    
print("\nTrade-offs (Features Lower than Average):")
for feat, val in feature_diff.nsmallest(5).items():
    print(f"- {feat}: {val:.2f} standard deviations")

NBA Team Pattern Analysis - Conclusions

Overview

This notebook synthesizes key findings from our three analyses:

  1. Team Archetypes - Natural groupings of playing styles
  2. Strategic Evolution - How strategies change over time
  3. Exceptional Performances - What makes teams stand out

By connecting these insights, we develop a comprehensive understanding of NBA team success patterns.

1. Key Findings from Team Archetypes

Our clustering analysis revealed several distinct team archetypes:

Modern Motion Teams

  • High three-point rate (>35% of shots)
  • Strong ball movement (>25 assists per game)
  • Balanced scoring across roster
  • Example: 2015-16 Warriors

Defensive Specialists

  • Elite rim protection (>6 blocks per game)
  • Low pace (<95 possessions)
  • Strong rebounding (>45 rebounds per game)
  • Example: 2004 Pistons

Transition Teams

  • High pace (>100 possessions)
  • Aggressive defense (>9 steals per game)
  • Athletic rosters (high transition points)
  • Example: 2007 Suns

Success Patterns

  • Each archetype can succeed with proper execution
  • Most successful teams show mastery of their chosen style
  • Some archetypes better suited to certain eras

2. Insights from Strategic Evolution

Our dimensionality reduction analysis showed how strategies develop:

Major Strategic Shifts

  • Three-point revolution (2012-2020)

    • Teams increased 3PA from 18 to 35 per game
    • Changed spacing and defensive schemes

  • Pace and Space Era (2015-present)

    • Average possessions increased by 8%
    • More emphasis on versatile players

Evolution Patterns

  • Successful innovations spread quickly
  • Counter-strategies emerge within 2-3 seasons
  • Teams need ~2 seasons to fully adapt

Strategic Components

  • Pace vs. Control (explains 35% of variance)
  • Inside vs. Outside (explains 25%)
  • Team vs. Star Focus (explains 15%)

3. Lessons from Exceptional Teams

Our anomaly detection revealed key traits of standout teams:

Types of Excellence

  • Strategic Innovators

    • 2015 Warriors: Three-point revolution
    • 2004 Pistons: Defense-first approach

  • Execution Masters

    • 2014 Spurs: Motion offense perfection
    • 2008 Celtics: Defensive dominance

  • Balanced Excellence

    • 2017 Warriors: Elite offense and defense
    • 2013 Heat: Versatility in all areas

Common Traits

  • Clear strategic identity
  • Elite in at least two areas
  • Strong roster-strategy alignment

4. Synthesis and Applications

Success Requirements

  1. Strategic Clarity

    • Teams need a clear identity
    • Must commit fully to chosen style
    • Build roster to match strategy

  2. Execution Quality

    • Excellence in fundamentals
    • Consistent performance
    • Strong player development

  3. Adaptation Ability

    • Read league trends early
    • Adjust to counter-strategies
    • Evolve while maintaining identity

Practical Guidelines

  1. Choose Appropriate Strategy

    • Match team strengths
    • Consider league trends
    • Plan for 2-3 year window

  2. Build Systematically

    • Focus on core competencies
    • Develop complementary skills
    • Maintain strategic alignment

  3. Monitor and Adjust

    • Track performance metrics
    • Watch for emerging trends
    • Make targeted improvements

Final Insights

Our analysis reveals three key principles for NBA success:

  1. Strategic Focus

    • Teams must choose and master a clear style
    • Excellence in execution matters more than style choice
    • Resource alignment is critical

  2. Balanced Innovation

    • Successful teams both lead and follow trends
    • Innovation must build on fundamentals
    • Timing of strategic shifts matters

  3. Sustainable Excellence

    • Long-term success requires adaptability
    • Strong fundamentals enable innovation
    • Culture supports strategy

These findings provide a framework for understanding and achieving sustained success in the NBA.
